<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="208" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[307,1140,1417,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">
The larval description presented here for 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gory and Percheron)" baseAuthorityName="Gory and Percheron" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[786,1018,1418,1439]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Hoplopyga singularis</emphasis>
(Gory and Percheron)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[495,559,1444,1465]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Brazil</collectingCountry>
is the second for the genus. 
<taxonomicName authority="(Gory and Percheron)" baseAuthorityName="Gory and Percheron" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis box="[891,1140,1444,1465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Hoplopyga brasiliensis</emphasis>
(Gory and Percheron)
</taxonomicName>
, also from 
<collectingCountry box="[677,743,1471,1492]" name="Brazil" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, was described by Vanin and Costa (1984) and reprinted in Costa 
<emphasis box="[627,681,1498,1519]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">et al.</emphasis>
(1988). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1880" box="[772,888,1498,1519]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[772,888,1498,1519]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Hoplopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
larvae are most similar morphologically to the larvae of 
<taxonomicName box="[667,849,1524,1545]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Argyripa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[667,761,1524,1545]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Argyripa</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
, but they are easily distinguished. In species of 
<emphasis box="[553,676,1551,1572]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1880" box="[553,672,1551,1572]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Hoplopyga</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
the last antennal segment has three dorsal sensory spots, and the dorsum of abdominal segment VII has two annulets. In species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1878" box="[424,518,1604,1625]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Argyripa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="207" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[424,518,1604,1625]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="207">Argyripa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
there are 10–15 dorsal sensory spots and the dorsum of abdominal segment VII has three annulets.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[279,1111,271,425]" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">
The genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1880" box="[423,539,271,292]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[423,539,271,292]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Hoplopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains about 20 species distributed from 
<collectingCountry box="[1004,1084,271,292]" name="Mexico" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Mexico</collectingCountry>
to 
<collectingCountry box="[279,386,297,318]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Argentina</collectingCountry>
, and it is currently being revised by Ratcliffe. Adults of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1880" box="[995,1111,298,319]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[995,1111,298,319]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Hoplopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have been collected from rotting fruits (especially plantains and bananas), resting on foliage, and in termite nests. Larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1880" box="[789,905,351,372]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[789,905,351,372]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Hoplopyga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are known to feed on rotting wood and other organic debris. 
<taxonomicName box="[749,981,378,399]" class="Insecta" family="Cetoniidae" genus="Hoplopyga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="208" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="singularis">
<emphasis box="[749,981,378,399]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Hoplopyga singularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is found in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[378,442,404,425]" name="Brazil" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and northern 
<collectingCountry box="[595,703,404,425]" name="Argentina" pageId="3" pageNumber="208">Argentina</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
